VALUES
(44, 5, 11, 19, 89, 7, 7, 'great fear came upon all the church', 'Fear in the Assembly', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of fear in relation to God and the assembly of believers. Acts 5:11 describes the fear that came upon the church, while Psalms 89:7 speaks of God being greatly to be feared in the assembly of the saints.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 11, 58, 12, 15, 15, 'great fear came upon all the church', 'Fear and Bitterness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear and its potential consequences within the community. Both passages emphasize the importance of vigilance to prevent negative influences, such as bitterness, from spreading and troubling many.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 12, 44, 19, 11, 11, 'by the hands of the apostles', 'Miracles by Apostolic Hands', 'Both passages emphasize the role of apostles in performing miracles. Acts 5:12 mentions ''signs and wonders'' by the apostles, while Acts 19:11 highlights ''special miracles by the hands of Paul.'' This connection highlights the continuity of divine power through the apostles.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 12, 47, 12, 12, 12, 'signs and wonders', 'Signs and Wonders of Apostles', 'Both passages emphasize the role of apostles in performing signs and wonders. Acts 5:12 describes these acts being done by the apostles, while 2 Corinthians 12:12 specifically refers to the signs of an apostle, linking their authority and miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 12, 58, 2, 4, 4, 'signs and wonders', 'Signs and Wonders Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of signs and wonders as evidence of God''s work among the people. Acts 5:12 highlights the apostles performing these acts, while Hebrews 2:4 speaks of God bearing witness through similar manifestations.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 12, 44, 14, 3, 3, 'signs and wonders', 'Signs and Wonders Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of apostles in performing signs and wonders. They highlight the divine empowerment given to the apostles to testify and perform miraculous acts.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 12, 45, 15, 19, 19, 'many signs and wonders', 'Signs and Wonders Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of ''signs and wonders'' in the ministry of the apostles and Paul. This connection highlights the continuity of miraculous acts as a means of validating the gospel message.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 12, 43, 10, 23, 23, 'Solomonâ€™s porch', 'Connection through Solomon''s Porch', 'Both passages emphasize Solomon''s porch as a significant location. In Acts, it is a place of miracles performed by the apostles, while in John, it is where Jesus walked, highlighting its importance in the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 12, 41, 16, 17, 18, 'many signs and wonders', 'Signs and Wonders Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the performance of signs and wonders by believers. Acts 5:12 describes the apostles performing many signs, while Mark 16:17-18 outlines the signs that will follow those who believe.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 13, 44, 2, 47, 47, 'but the people magnified them', 'Church Growth and Favor', 'Both passages emphasize the favor of the people towards the apostles and the church. Acts 5:13 highlights that the people magnified the apostles, while Acts 2:47 notes that the church had favor with all the people, leading to daily additions to the church.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 13, 44, 4, 21, 21, 'the people magnified them', 'Public Response to Apostolic Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s reaction to the apostles. In Acts 4:21, the people glorified God for the apostles'' actions, while in Acts 5:13, the people magnified them, indicating a growing respect and admiration.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 13, 43, 12, 42, 42, 'but the people magnified them', 'Fear of Social Repercussions', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of social exclusion. In Acts, people refrained from joining the apostles, while in John, rulers believed but did not confess due to fear of being put out of the synagogue.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 13, 43, 19, 38, 38, 'but the people magnified them', 'Fear and Secrecy in Discipleship', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear among Jesus'' followers. In Acts, the fear of joining the apostles is evident, while in John, Joseph of Arimathea''s secret discipleship reflects a similar apprehension.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 13, 4, 17, 12, 13, NULL, 'Fear of Divine Presence', 'This connection highlights the fear of approaching the divine. In Acts, people are hesitant to join the apostles, paralleling the Israelites'' fear of approaching the tabernacle in Numbers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 13, 4, 24, 8, 10, 'the people magnified them', 'Blessing and Cursing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of blessing and cursing, where the people magnify the apostles in Acts, paralleling how Balaam''s blessings in Numbers highlight God''s favor. The connection illustrates the power of divine endorsement in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 13, 9, 16, 4, 5, NULL, 'Fear and Reverence in Worship', 'Both passages emphasize the fear and reverence shown by people in response to divine authority. In Acts, the people magnified the apostles, while in 1 Samuel, the elders trembled at Samuel''s arrival, indicating a similar recognition of holiness. This connection highlights the communal response to God''s chosen representatives.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 14, 44, 2, 47, 47, NULL, 'Growth of the Early Church', 'Both passages emphasize the addition of believers to the church. Acts 5:14 notes that ''believers were the more added,'' paralleling Acts 2:47''s mention of the Lord adding to the church daily.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 14, 23, 55, 11, 13, 'added to the Lord', 'Growth and Fulfillment of God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the theme of growth and fulfillment in both passages. Acts 5:14 speaks of believers being added to the Lord, while Isaiah 55:11 emphasizes that God''s word will accomplish its purpose, leading to joy and transformation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 14, 44, 4, 4, 4, 'added to the Lord', 'Growth of Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the increase in believers following the preaching of the word. Acts 4:4 notes about five thousand men believed, while Acts 5:14 mentions multitudes of both men and women being added.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 14, 15, 10, 1, 1, 'multitudes both of men and women', 'Congregation of Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of men and women in response to spiritual leadership. In Acts, believers are added to the Lord, while in Ezra, a great congregation assembles due to Ezra''s prayer and confession.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 14, 2, 35, 22, 22, NULL, 'Connection of Willing Hearts', 'Both passages emphasize the participation of men and women in contributing to the Lord. Acts 5:14 notes believers being added, while Exodus 35:22 highlights those who were willing-hearted bringing offerings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 14, 5, 29, 11, 12, 'believers were the more added', 'Covenant and Community Growth', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of diverse groups in a covenantal relationship with God. Acts 5:14 highlights the growth of believers, while Deuteronomy 29:11-12 mentions various members of the community entering into covenant with the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 14, 5, 31, 11, 12, 'men and women', 'Gathering of Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of people, specifically men and women, to hear and learn about God. Acts 5:14 mentions the addition of believers, while Deuteronomy 31:11-12 calls for a collective assembly to hear the law.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 15, 40, 14, 36, 36, 'the shadow of Peter passing by', 'Healing Through Proximity', 'Both passages emphasize the power of proximity to holy figures for healing. In Acts, the shadow of Peter is sought for healing, while in Matthew, touching the hem of Jesus'' garment is desired for wholeness.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 15, 44, 19, 11, 12, 'the sick', 'Miraculous Healings by Apostles', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healings performed by the apostles, highlighting the power of God working through them. The use of physical objects, such as Peter''s shadow and Paul''s handkerchiefs, illustrates a common theme of divine healing.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 15, 43, 14, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Healing and Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the power of faith in healing. In Acts, the shadow of Peter brings healing, while in John, believers are promised to perform greater works through faith.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 15, 40, 9, 21, 21, NULL, 'Healing Through Touch', 'Both passages emphasize the power of touch for healing. In Acts, the shadow of Peter is believed to bring healing, while in Matthew, touching Jesus'' garment is seen as a means to be made whole.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 16, 41, 16, 17, 18, NULL, 'Healing and Belief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of the sick as a sign of belief in Jesus. Acts 5:16 describes the healing of many, while Mark 16:18 states that believers will lay hands on the sick and they shall recover.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 16, 41, 2, 3, 4, 'bringing sick folks', 'Healing and Faith in Action', 'Both passages emphasize the act of bringing the sick to Jesus for healing. In Acts, a multitude brings sick folks to be healed, while in Mark, four men bring a paralyzed man to Jesus, showcasing the communal effort in seeking healing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 16, 40, 4, 24, 24, 'them which were vexed with unclean spirits', 'Healing Miracles Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of sick individuals and those possessed by unclean spirits. They illustrate the widespread response to Jesus and the apostles, highlighting their miraculous abilities to heal.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
